0px 5px;">Dark trading</h2> </td> </tr> </table> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">The traditional way to invest was that you would pick the stocks you wan=
ted to own, you would go to the stock exchange, and you would buy them. Thi=
s was, you hoped, good for you: You paid the market price for the stocks th=
at you thought would go up. But you were also participating in a collective=
 process that was good for everyone else. By picking stocks, you were doing=
 your part to allocate capital to its best uses: The stocks that everyone p=
icked would go up, making it easier for those companies to raise money to d=
o worthwhile things; the stocks that nobody picked would go down, and they =
would have to stop doing the worthless things they had been doing.</p> <p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You were also doing your part to make the pricing=
=C2=A0of stocks efficient: Everyone competed to find out relevant informati=
on and to figure out how it might affect companies, and so those companies=
=E2=80=99 stock prices reflected all of the relevant information. The compa=
nies=E2=80=99 stock prices were =E2=80=9Cright,=E2=80=9D or at least as rig=
ht as everyone could make them.=C2=A0</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mode=
rn markets have become, in many ways, more efficient, not in the stock-mark=
et-efficiency sense of the word but in the regular sense: You can do more s=
tuff faster, and you can get exactly what you want. One thing that this mea=
ns is that now you can=C2=A0<em>unbundle=C2=A0</em>the =E2=80=9Cbuying stoc=
ks that are good for me=E2=80=9D part of investing from the =E2=80=9Cpartic=
ipating in a collective process that creates social goods=E2=80=9D part. Yo=
u can free-ride on the collective process.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>People talk about this a lot=C2=A0with index funds. The thesis of an index=
 fund is that a lot of smart hard-working people compete to pick the best s=
tocks. As a product of their competition, all the stocks are pretty fairly =
priced; if they weren=E2=80=99t, those smart hard-working competitors would=
 buy the underpriced ones and sell the overpriced ones. So=C2=A0<em>you=C2=
=A0</em>can just opt out of that competition: You buy <em>all</em> the stoc=
ks at their market prices, trusting that everyone else's hard work will mak=
e the prices right. And so you will be able to buy long-term economic growt=
h at the right price. This is nice for you, but if=C2=A0<em>everyone=C2=A0<=
/em>did it, it would be bad: <a href=3D"https://links.message.bloomberg.com=
